Several days ago Microsoft released <a href="http://support.microsoft.com/kb/2924386/en-us" target="_blank">Rollup 1 for Windows Azure Pack</a>. The KB article describes how to update your WAP deployment.

## <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>The Issue</strong></span>

I strictly followed the upgrade guide, and so far it went very well. But after upgrading the Admin API and Admin Site components, I was not able to launch the admin site and received a well known security message which you usually get after initial deployment when the security token of the installation account is not updated and you didn&#8217;t re-login.

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="402" height="134" /> 

As I was pretty sure that I was able to access the Windows Auth Site with the same user before the upgrade ðŸ™‚ , so I started my investigations. The RTM version of Windows Azure Pack adds the user account which is used to deploy the components to a local group on the WAP server, where the Admin API and Admin Site are deployed. The group is called : **MgmtSvc Operators**

Because I modified the group by removing the user and adding a AD Security Group I was comfortable to add additional WAP Admins. But hey.. where has this local group gone?

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="468" height="399" /> 

RU1 added two new local groups called **WindowsFabricAdministrators** and **WindowsFabricAllowedUsers**. While the first seems to reflect WAP Admins, the second seems to restrict Admin API connection permissions, but not sure on that yet.

Having a look at the corresponding table within the MgmtSvc database has shown me the root cause.

<img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," width="583" height="265" /> 

The previously used local group was still registered, not so the new Fabric Management groups.

## <span style="text-decoration: underline;">The Solution</span>

Of course you could modifiy the table manually using SQL Management Studio, but it is not supported AFAIK.

I therefore used the CMDLETs Get-MgmtSvcAdminUser andÂ  Add-MgmtSvcAdminUser from the MgmtSvc Modules.

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Show current WAP Admins</strong></span>

<pre>$connectionstring = 'Server=srvdb01.miru.local\SysCtr;Initial Catalog=Microsoft.MgmtSvc.Store;User ID=sa;Password=Some@Password'
Get-MgmtSvcAdminUserÂ  -ConnectionString $connectionstring</pre>

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Add a principal (group or user) as WAP Admin</strong></span>

<pre>$connectionstring = 'Server=srvdb01.miru.local\SysCtr;Initial Catalog=Microsoft.MgmtSvc.Store;User ID=sa;Password=Some@Password'
Add-MgmtSvcAdminUser -ConnectionString $connectionstring -Principal 'DOMAIN\SecurityGroupName'</pre>

I decided to use a Domain Security Group, so I should not be affected by any changes to the local groups in the future ðŸ™‚

Beside this little hick up, the RU1 upgrade went very well and smooth.
